 In 1973, Congress enacted HN2[
] the Health Maintenance Organization Act, 42 USC § 300(e), to facilitate the formation and operation of HMOs by making federal financial assistance available and preempting state laws that interferred with their 
operation.  Congress specifically authorized "closed panel" HMOs.

 The corporations involved in this action are: Tivoli Enterprises, Inc.; Vanilla Chip Ice Cream Co.; Sullock Corporation; 
Sacramento Mighty Good Ice Cream Co.; Caledonia Ice Cream Co.; Foothills Ice Cream Works, Ltd.; Green Mountain Ice 
Cream Co., Inc.; Idaho Ices, Inc.; The Inside Scoop, Inc.; and ICE, Inc.

 Fed. R. Civ. P. 13(b) HN8[
] states that a counterclaim is permissive if it does "not aris[e] out of the transaction or occurrence 
that is the subject matter of the opposing party's claim."

 See also Times-Picayune Publishing Co. v. United States, 345 U.S. 594, 626, 73 S. Ct. 872, 889, 97 L. Ed. 1277 (1953); 
American Tobacco Co. v. United States, 328 U.S. 781, 789, 66 S. Ct. 1125, 1129, 90 L. Ed. 1575 (1946); V. & L. Cicione, Inc. v. 
C. Schmidt & Sons, Inc., 403 F. Supp. 643, 651 (E.D. Pa. 1975), aff'd without opinion, 565 F.2d 154 (3d Cir. 1977).

 The Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. section 1 states in pertinent part: HN3[
] Every contract, combination in the form of trust or otherwise, or conspiracy, in restraint of trade or commerce 
among the several States, . . . is hereby declared to be illegal.

 Both parties' economic experts defined variable costs as those costs which rise in direct proportion to sales. Record at 6-117; 
12-176. The determination as to which costs are fixed and which costs are variable is a factual determination. William Inglis, 
668 F.2d at 1038.

 HN21[
] Section 17043 states: It is unlawful for any person engaged in business within this State to sell any article at less than the cost thereof to such vendor . 
. . for the purpose of injuring competitors or destroying competition.

 HN22[
] Section 17044 states: It is unlawful for any person engaged in business within this State to seller use any article or product as a "loss leader" . . HN23[
] Cal. Bus. & Prof. Code § 17030 defines a "loss leader" as: any article or product sold at less than cost: (a) Where the purpose is to induce, promote or encourage the purchase of other 
merchandise; . . . (c) Where the effect is to divert trade from or otherwise injure competitors.

 HN24[
] Cal. Bus. & Prof. Code § 17026 sets forth the relevant definition of costs as to Ken Carter: "Cost" as applied to distribution means the invoice . . . cost of the article or product to the distributor and vendor, plus the cost of 
doing business by the distributor and vendor.

 Sammi's costs would differ from those of Ken Carter; HN25[
] Cal. Bus. & Prof. Code § 17026 states: "Cost" as applied to production includes the cost of raw materials, labor and all overhead expenses of the producer. To the extent that Sammi and Ken Carter are treated as a single economic entity, it would be more rational to use the cost of 
production in lieu of the invoice cost applicable to distributors.

 Section 5(a)(1) of the Federal Trade Commission Act, 38 Stat. 719, as amended, 15 U.S.C. § 45(a)(1), provides: HN1[
] "Unfair methods of competition in or affecting commerce, and unfair or deceptive acts or practices in or affecting commerce, are declared unlawful." The First Amendment to the Constitution provides: HN2[
] "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or 
abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the 
Government for a redress of grievances."

 La.C.C. Art. 1995 HN3[
] provides that damages in a breach of contract action "are measured by the loss sustained by the 
obligee and the profit of which he has been deprived."

 HN1[
] Section 337 prohibits unfair methods of competition and unfair acts in the importation of goods into the United States including the infringement of patents and trademarks. See 19 U.S.C. § 1337. Section 337 cases are adjudicated through an 
administrative process under the jurisdiction of the ITC. Id. § 1337(c).
